between 1902 and 1945 in classrooms from Canada to Hong Kong, from the West Indies to Australia. Moser argues that these photographs played a central role in the invention and representation of imperial citizenship. She shows how citizenship became a photographable and teachable subject by tracing the intended readings of the images that the committee hoped to impart to viewers and analyzing how spectators may have used their encounters with these photographs for protest and resistance. Interweaving political and economic history, history of pedagogy, and theories of citizenship with a consideration of the aesthetic and affective dimensions of viewing the lectures, Projecting Citizenship offers important insights into the social inequalities and visual language of colonial rule.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCitizenshipzGreat BritainxColoniesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhotography in educationxColonieszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhotographyxPolitical aspectszGreat BritainxColoniesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPhotography / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271082875zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271082875423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271082875.jpg  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK